<TEXT>
the navy has equipment capable of recovering the 
cargo door that sank in 16800 feet of water after tearing away from 
a united airlines jumbo jet an undersea technician said 
the national transportation safety board has not decided whether 
to attempt to recover the door from the pacific ocean 85 miles 
southwest of honolulu said member lee dickinson he said however 
that examining the front cargo door would be very helpful to us in 
our analysis 
navy radar tracked a large object falling into the ocean about 45 
seconds after the pilot of uniteds flight 811 reported an inflight 
emergency early friday soon after taking off for auckland new 
zealand dickinson said tuesday night 
investigators suspect the cargo door popped open at 22000 feet 
tearing away with a large section of fuselage nine passengers 
seated on the right side of the boeing 747 jet were swept to their 
deaths 
the first lawsuits stemming from the accident were filed here 
wednesday 
mae s sapolu a united flight attendant from honolulu filed a 
state court lawsuit seeking unspecified damages from boeing co 
maker of the jumbo jet 
according to court documents sapolu was serving drinks in 
business class when the hole opened in the right side of the 
aircraft sapolu said she was thrown to the floor and had to cling 
to the leg of a seat to keep from being swept out of the plane 
edwin geoffrey tudor a passenger from new south wales australia 
also sought unspecified damages in his lawsuit filed in us 
district court accusing from united and boeing of neglect in 
maintaining the boeing 747 
sapolu and tudor said they suffered physical injuries and 
emotional distress 
capt david m cronin turned the crippled jet around and flew it 
100 miles on two of four engines landing safely at honolulu 
international airport 
the radar picked up something that could be a large piece of 
metal possibly the cargo door dickinson said 
that information is going back to washington dc to see if 
we can indeed determine that was the cargo door and its exact 
location 
we have the location at the surface of the water he said 
youre talking about three miles down one can only guess where 
that is 
paul wolcott a technician and submersible launch pilot at the 
university of hawaiis hawaii undersea research laboratory said it 
would be difficult but probably not impossible to find the cargo 
door 
a search for the door probably would begin with a towed 
underwater sonar sled to determine possible locations of the door 
and then the use of a remote operation vehicle equipped with a 
camera to pinpoint the location wolcott said wednesday 
the navy has rovs capable of hooking a line to the door so it 
could be pulled to the surface he said 
the least likely possibility because of the tremendous expense 
involved would be the use of the navys san diegobased sea cliff 
one of the worlds few manned submersibles capable of reaching that 
depth wollcott said 
dickinson said the ntsbs field work was nearly completed and 
investigators would leave hawaii by thursday 
jim guyette uniteds executive vice president for operations 
said the damaged jetliner will be repaired although there was no 
estimate on when it will be returned to service 
the air frame will be fixed in hawaii and the engines will be 
repaired in san francisco guyette told a news conference here 
wednesday 
about 10 of the passengers who were on flight 811 remain in 
hawaii as well as a few survivors of the missing and united is 
paying all expenses guyette said 
two united flight attendants are the only ones on the plane who 
remain hospitalized 
</TEXT>
