<TEXT>
federal reserve chairman alan greenspan defends 
his decision to fight inflation with higher interest rates even 
though the bush administration disagrees with the central banks 
reading of the economy 
greenspan told the senate budget committee on tuesday that the 
current inflation rate is not doing clear significant corrosive 
harm to the economy at the moment 
but it has built into it the seeds of an acceleration that if 
not dampened can become very damaging he said in his first 
public statement since the federal reserve escalated its 
antiinflation fight friday by increasing a key bank lending rate 
he said the central bank expects inflation to increase this year 
to the 45 percent to 5 percent range up about half a percentage 
point from last year 
however fed policy makers are worried that a pickup in wage 
increases and rising material costs will cause businesses and 
consumers to include the expectation of inflation in their plans 
when that happens prices will rise faster he said 
our basic goal is to make sure that inflation does not 
accelerate inordinately and ultimately phases down he said 
treasury secretary nicholas f brady in testimony before the 
house budget committee softened previous criticism of federal 
reserve tightening but he did not retract his statement that the 
administration sees less danger of inflation 
its two people looking at the same statistic and coming to a 
slightly different conclusion brady said 
greenspan while not explicitly acknowledging the 
administrations comments said in response to a question from sen 
william l armstrong rcolo i think i get it from all sides 
in the budget committee sen william armstrong rcolo and 
sen james exon dneb praised the fed for its stance toward 
inflation but sen don nickles rokla told greenspan im 
afraid youre laying the seeds for a recession 
sen pete domenici rnm said he believed the feds strategy 
of gradual increases in interest rates would not work and that far 
more ratcheting down of the economy will be needed to achieve the 
feds stated goal of zero inflation 
youve got to almost create a selffulfilling prophecy and 
create a recession he said 
brady greenspan and white house budget director richard darman 
who spoke to the senate appropriations committee all said that 
congress and the administration can help the fed curb inflation and 
also permit interest rates to drop by agreeing on a credible plan to 
cut the budget deficit 
greenspan said president bushs budget if adopted would trigger 
lower interest rates even if it eventually produced a deficit higher 
than the 100 billion grammrudman target for 1990 
i may say i would like to see grammrudmanhollings targets met 
literally but i dont think that is required to bring a 
significant reduction in interest rates he said 
if after the fact the real number is 110 billion or 120 
billion in that vein i would think that would be a major 
improvement which the markets would take very positively the 
federal reserve chairman said 
but the reduction from the 1989 deficit of about 165 billion 
must not be accomplished with accounting tricks and must hold out 
the reasonable prospect for further reductions he said 
what cannot have a positive effect is finding some set of 
bookkeeping gimmicks which largely meet grammrudman for fiscal 1990 
and then paper over 91 92 93 he said 
