measles has hit some colleges this winter but 
federal health officials said outbreaks of the disease normally 
associated with childhood are scattered and no cause for great alarm 
students lined up for measles vaccine last week at the cw post 
campus of new yorks long island university and free inoculations 
were offered this week at the university of texas 
a measles outbreak caused catawba college in salisbury nc to 
cancel its basketball season and ohios kent state university 
stopped sending nursing students to local hospitals for fear of 
giving patients measles 
were definitely having measles outbreaks right now but it is 
unfortunately nothing new said dr diane simpson of the us 
centers for disease controls immunization division we do get 
outbreaks on college campuses and high school campuses each year 
most states require children to be inoculated for measles before 
entering school but some still reach college without immunity 
in some cases simpson said the vaccine doesnt take in others 
colleges may not have required proof of immunization 
at cw post where 19 cases were reported as of monday 
immunization rules are now being strictly enforced said spokeswoman 
mary ring 
measles cases at siena college in new york and the university of 
hartford in connecticut prompted the east coast athletic conference 
to ban spectators from the scheduled march 911 basketball 
tournament 
measles can be transmitted easily at colleges because of close 
living quarters said valerie cox assistant director for nursing 
services at the university of texas 
only three cases have been reported at the university of texas 
but 154 cases were reported recently in lubbock many of them in 
public schools and at texas tech university where the outbreak 
prompted immunization of 5200 students 
the cdc also reported measles at bradley university in illinois 
through last week 244 measles cases had been reported nationwide 
since jan 1 up from 204 at the same time last year according to 
cdc statistics 
but simpson said those figures may not reflect the recent college 
outbreaks or other recent outbreaks among younger children 
measles or rubeola is usually marked by a rash fever cough 
congestion and red sensitive eyes complications can occur without 
proper treatment 
in the late 1970s cdc measles specialists believed the once 
common childhood disease could be eradicated in the united states by 
fall 1982 but in the last six years 1497 to 6282 cases have been 
reported annually 
