two boxcars loaded with radioactive waste were en 
route today from the rocky flats nuclear weapons plant to a 
temporary storage site in idaho relieving a waste buildup that 
threatened to close the plant 
idaho gov cecil andrus who in october closed his state to 
shipments of radioactive waste lifted his ban on thursday he said 
he would allow two boxcars a month for six months to unload at the 
department of energys idaho national energy laboratory in idaho 
falls 
andrus cited national security interests rocky flats operated 
for the department of energy by rockwell international produces 
plutonium triggers for nuclear weapons 
the plant 17 miles from denver could have been shut down as early 
as this month gov roy romer in october threatened to close it when 
it reached its waste storage capacity 
the boxcars which rocky flats spokesman ed heintz said left 
tuesday for a trip that takes seven to nine days contained 150 
cubic yards of clothing and equipment contaminated with small 
amounts of plutonium 
were real pleased to get it out heintz said this gives 
us another six months breathing room to work on a permanent 
solution with doe and congress 
before tuesday 1332 cubic yards of waste had piled up at the 
plant which is under a stateimposed limit of 1601 cubic yards of 
storage 
one hundredfifty cubic yards is about a months worth of waste 
generated under current plant production levels when rocky flats is 
operating at full capacity it generates 200 to 250 cubic yards of 
waste each month 
last week romer said he would allow rocky flats to continue 
operations until late this year depending on how much waste is 
generated there 
romer and andrus are pushing department of energy officials to 
meet a target date of sept 1 for the opening of the waste isolation 
pilot plant near carlsbad nm for permanent storage of nuclear 
waste 
