<TEXT>
for decades venezuelans dreamed that 
oil would cure the economic woes of their petroleumrich country 
that illusion held even after oil prices began to plummet 
appears to have ended with the worst violence in venezuela in 31 
years 
increases of 30 percent to 50 percent in public transport tariffs 
and price gouging by bus drivers acted as a detonator for an economy 
in rapid deterioration 
the slide in the price of oil which accounts for 90 percent of 
venezuelan export revenue coupled with a suffocating 33 billion 
foreign debt 
the nation pocketed an estimated 9 billion in oil revenues last 
year compared to 19 billion in 1981 
inflation this year is expected to reach 70 percent up from 35 
percent last year 
president carlos andres perez who took power three weeks ago 
announced a sweeping economic reform package intended to breathe 
life into the stagnant economy and persuade international bankers to 
increase loans to the country 
some of those reforms included freeing interest rates doubling 
gasoline prices and establishing a freefloating currency with a 
consequent increase in the price of imports 
the violence that erupted across the nation monday showed the 
difficulty the government will have implementing the economic 
reforms 
the reforms were backed by the international monetary fund from 
which perez hopes to obtain a 15 billion shortterm loan 
until now venezuela had avoided turning to the imf for a 
bailout perez himself called the organization the equivalent of 
economic totalitarianism venezuela has 18 million inhabitants 
and was for years an island of tranquility in a sea of regional 
violence political instability and economic recession 
under perezs first administration from 1973 to 1978 oil prices 
boomed and the country enjoyed an unparalleled prosperity there was 
full employment and inflation did not break single digits 
those memories were enough to guarantee perez a landslide victory 
in the election dec4 say political experts 
perez evoked for venezuelans a bonanza and now theyve had a 
rude awakening said sociologist and university professor anibal 
romero 
