<TEXT>
americans personal income shot up 18 percent 
in january the biggest increase in more than a year while the pace 
of consumer spending was nearly flat after a strong gain in 
december the government reported today 
the commerce department said income rose 74 billion to a 
seasonally adjusted annual rate of 428 trillion in january 
following a 09 percent increase in december and a 02 percent drop 
in november 
januarys income gain was the biggest monthly increase since a 2 
percent jump in october 1987 
personal consumption spending meanwhile edged up just 01 
percent in january to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 335 
trillion following a 08 percent gain in december and a 04 percent 
jump during november the figures include virtually all consumer 
spending except interest payments on debt 
januarys 01 percent increase was the weakest performance for 
consumer spending since a 15 percent decrease last september 
a slowdown in consumer spending would be welcome news because of 
worries that demand has been outstripping the production 
capabilities of factories coping with high operating rates and tight 
labor markets 
the increase in income was paced by a 12 percent gain in the key 
component of wages and salaries reflecting continued strong 
employment 
the recent income gains were bolstered by several special 
factors including a 41 percent pay raise in january for federal 
civilian and military personnel a 4 percent costofliving increase 
in social security benefits in january and a december increase in 
farm subsidy payments the commerce department said 
but even excluding such special factors personal income still 
increased 16 percent in january and 08 percent in december 
americans disposable or aftertax incomes rose 17 percent in 
january after rising 09 percent in december and falling 03 
percent in november 
with the income gain strongly outpacing the rise in spending the 
personal savings rate savings as a percentage of disposable income 
rose to 58 percent from 43 percent in december 
spending was held back by a 3 percent decrease in spending on 
durable goods big ticket items expected to last at least three 
years purchases of services which includes housing costs were up 
05 percent purchases of nondurable goods rose 09 percent 
</TEXT>
