<TEXT>
south carolina today banned hazardous waste 
shipments from 32 states and puerto rico that have not begun 
creating their own dumps 
as trucks that come from an area thats banned were going 
to turn the truck back and if at all possible escort them back to 
the state line said bill culler of the state department of health 
and environmental control 
the ban applied to a commercial landfill operated here by gsx 
services it is one of only two commercial hazardous waste landfills 
in the southeast 
most landfill customers had been notified of the ban but the 
department increased the number of inspectors monitoring the 
landfill from three to 10 today to watch for unexpected loads from 
banned states culler said 
it will have a tremendous impact on our business gsx vice 
president roger davis said we just think its a good business 
decision not to challenge it 
the ban announced tuesday affects such heavy landfill users as 
florida and north carolina 
it results from gov carroll campbells jan 18 executive order 
that south carolina would prohibit beginning march 1 the disposal 
of waste from any state that refused to dispose of the waste itself 
we hope our actions will encourage other states to move toward 
developing their own hazardous waste management programs said 
hartsill truesdale head of the state health departments hazardous 
waste division 
it was both the failure of other states to aggressively address 
their waste disposal problems and the growing imbalance in waste 
disposal that prompted governor campbell to issue this executive 
order 
the massive gsx landfill on the shore of lake marion annually 
accepts 135000 tons of hazardous waste such as solvents acids and 
other chemical garbage about 70 percent comes from out of state 
the other hazardous waste landfill in the southeast is in emelle 
ala 
the governors spokesman tucker eskew said he believed 
campbells message to other states would come across if its not 
good enough for you its not good enough for us 
campbell has said that any state would have to remove disposal 
prohibitions before the ban could be lifted 
north carolina responded to the ban with the introduction of a 
bill tuesday that renews that states search for a hazardous waste 
treatment plant though it fails to specify when a site would be 
chosen 
south carolina state sen phil leventis a longtime landfill 
opponent said other states should have working disposal sites 
before being allowed to send south carolina their waste 
anybody that promises us that with a little revision of a law 
that their state is soon going to be handling its own hazardous 
waste is simply telling us the check is in the mail leventis said 
the banned states shipped about 45 percent of the waste handled 
by the dump in 1987 according to the latest figures available 
in addition to puerto rico florida and north carolina the 
following states are affected by the ban alaska arizona 
california colorado idaho illinois indiana iowa kansas 
louisiana maine mississippi missouri nebraska new hampshire 
new mexico north dakota ohio oklahoma oregon pennsylvania 
rhode island south dakota tennessee utah vermont washington 
west virginia wisconsin and wyoming 
</TEXT>
