<TEXT>
a court has acquitted two missionaries 
from the united states and canada on charges of proselytizing and 
they said after spending four months in prison awaiting trial that 
they want to leave the hindu kingdom as soon as possible 
weve had enough of nepal david mcbride of columbia pa 
told the associated press on wednesday we are going to go home 
mcbride and mervyn budd of london ontario were acquitted 
tuesday on charges of preaching christianity and causing a 
disturbance to hinduism 
mcbride 33 and budd 26 arrived wednesday in katmandu from the 
town of phidim 150 miles to the east where they were arrested oct 
27 at the end of a fiveweek trek of the himalayan foothills 
they were arrested on charges of proselytizing punishable by up 
to six years in prison 
the constitution declares that nepal is a hindu state and the 
law bans conversion from hinduism to another religion 
mcbride and budd had pleaded innocent the court ordered them 
held because nepalese law does not permit bail for foreigners who 
face sentences of more than six months 
police had confiscated books on christianity in the nepali 
limbu sherpa tibetan english and german languages as well as 
cassette tapes they allegedly sold during their trek 
justice ek raj acharya acquitted them because of lack of evidence 
mcbrides wife connie embraced him after he arrived by plane in 
katmandu 
for me it is a miracle that they are released she said 
i am happy to be out mcbride said but there are a lot of 
people that need to be out of that jail too 
he said at least twothirds of the 46 others in the prison were 
innocent at least that is what i think from my conversations with 
them they are not guilty but they have staying longer than me 
some of them cant afford lawyers some of them just stay there 
mcbride and budd were affiliated with the operation mobilization 
a londonbased christian organization 
an official with the organization mike wakely said the two had 
received 2000 cards and letters from all over the world while in 
jail on tuesday alone he said they received 243 letters 
their 90day visas expired while they were in prison but 
officials were working to clear the paperwork so they could leave 
nepal 
this will be just a formality they would be free to go 
home according to an official who spoke on condition of 
anonymity 
last month three hindus who converted to christianity were 
sentenced to one year in prison by a court in bhadrapur 190 miles 
southeast of katmandu a nepalese news agency reported 
