the bush administration missed two more 
congressional deadlines wednesday for staking out positions on major 
defense issues saying it wasnt ready to produce reports dealing 
with star wars and the b2 stealth bomber 
col miguel monteverde a pentagon spokesman said acting defense 
secretary william h taft iv was notifying congress that the march 1 
deadline for the star wars report would be missed because the future 
of the antimissile defense system is being addressed in a much 
broader white house strategic policy review 
the air force in a brief statement said the report on the b2 
would not go forward wednesday because it was still in 
coordination 
an air force official who asked not to be named said however 
that that report also was being delayed until the national security 
review was completed 
president bush in his budget address to congress announced last 
month he had ordered the broad policy review and said he expected it 
to be completed within 90 days 
on feb 15 the white house cited the same review as the reason 
it would not meet a deadline for choosing between two mobile nuclear 
missiles the singlewarhead midgetman or a railcar version of the 
10warhead mx 
the missed deadlines come at the same time bush has been unable 
to win senate confirmation of his choice as defense secretary 
former sen john tower of texas 
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater and other administration 
officials have insisted that towers troubles are not responsible 
for the failure to meet the congressional deadlines 
rather they assert that those deadlines were set much too early 
for a new administration and that bush wants to take the time to 
review the nations entire strategic posture 
other officials at the pentagon however say little in the way 
of policy formation is being accomplished at the defense department 
because of the lack of leadership those officials holdovers from 
the reagan administration spoke on the condition of anonymity 
the first report that had been due wednesday dealt with one 
deployment option for a star wars system the socalled alps or 
accidental launch protection system 
first suggested by sen sam nunn dga the chairman of the 
senate armed services committee alps would entail the construction 
of a small missiledefense system capable of stopping a missile 
fired by accident or by a terrorist group 
the second report due wednesday involved the air forces b2 a 
new bomber that is supposed to be almost invisible to radar the 
first of the bombers was unveiled in november but has not yet flown 
the air force wants to build 132 of the planes but estimated in 
december that counting research and development costs the bombers 
would cost more than 500 million each even if research and 
development expenses are discounted each plane will cost 305 
million to build 
faced with that kind of expense congress said it wanted a report 
by march 1 setting forth the total program cost in constant and 
in current dollars of the advanced technology b2 bomber program 
