<DOCNO> AP890301-0145 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
here are excerpts from the majority and 
minority reports of the national economic commission which were 
submitted to president bush and congressional leaders wednesday 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 
as the united states approaches the 1990s and with the economy 
continuing to expand dynamically economic policy shaped to some 
extent by the federal reserve should be designed not only to 
sustain economic growth in the near term but to help create the 
national wealth that will be the basis for future growth 
budget deficits are a direct drain on the national savings pool 
to enable investment to grow rapidly either private savings must 
increase or the necessary capital must be borrowed from abroad 
nonetheless the decade of the 1980s has been characterized by 
high savings and low spending in most industrial countries 
contrasted with low savings and high spending in the united states 
including that by the federal government such imbalances cannot be 
sustained indefinitely 
one result of these spendingsavings imbalances has been 
historically large trade deficits in the united states and 
correspondingly large trade surpluses in a number of other 
countries large trade deficits like budget deficits drain 
domestic savings as more and more of the income produced in the 
united states flows abroad one factor causing trade deficits is 
that american consumers like to buy foreign goods including capital 
equipment american manufacturers should become more competitive and 
regain the favor of the us marketplace 
another objective is to increase investment relative to 
consumption in the economy one of the best ways to accomplish this 
is to adopt the recommendation that the capital gains tax be sharply 
cut 
recent data suggests that the industrialized countries are 
becoming more capital intensive the country that is the farthest 
along in this process japan has a rate of productivity growth that 
is almost twice that of the united states with real income growth 
also twice as high 
americans must significantly increase savings that in turn will 
be used to finance capital investment clearly one task is to 
reduce the budget deficits and factors that result in the federal 
government being a drain on the national saving pool and to do so 
without raising taxes this should reduce the real cost of capital 
and stimulate even more investment demand 
the next step is to set a course for creating government 
surpluses or at least inhibiting future government deficits while at 
the same time not inhibiting economic growth this will be a long 
term process 
whatever the benefits of deficit reduction the nation must not 
expect that a balanced budget or even government surpluses will 
solve all our economic problems 
comparing the economic performance of the key industrial 
countries over the past 15 years does not suggest that countries 
with the lowest budget deficits are those that necessarily grow the 
fastest have the lowest inflation have the highest savings rates 
have the lowest real interest rates or the lowest trade deficits 
there are many other factors besides balanced budgets that could 
contribute to economic growth rapidly changing technology and 
products newly productive economic centers and increasingly 
integrated world markets suggest that an economic policy driven by a 
single goal is not appropriate 
economic policy should not only address the traditional concerns 
about capital investment and productivity in the industrial sector 
but also such hardtomeasure items as productivity in service 
industries and educated labor forces 
the budget should and will be balanced over time indeed the 
administrations budget lays out one workable plan for eliminating 
the deficit 
there are other alternatives reflecting different priorities but 
with equal or greater spending restraint that could balance the 
budget by fiscal 1993 as required by grammrudmanhollings grh 
without raising taxes 
the national economic commission has been working on this project 
for approximately 11 months we have heard from 85 witnesses and 
read over 1300 responses from private citizens and groups our 
mandate was to recommend ways to eliminate the budget deficit while 
not impeding economic growth 
it is clear that the president would prefer to coordinate this 
activity with congress on a onetoone basis indeed this is the 
manner in which this process should proceed 
we should continue to reduce the deficit as a percentage of gnp 
we support the position that the deficit can be resolved through 
restraints on the growth of federal spending without increasing 
taxes or affecting low income meanstested benefits therefore we 
recommend restraining spending increases while keeping growth strong 
as the mainstay of budget policy 
with an estimated 82 billion in additional revenues in fiscal 
year 1990 it is clear that we do not have to and should not raise 
taxes but rather should restrain the rate of growth in federal 
spending 
the grammrudmanhollings deficit targets represent arbitrary but 
appropriate goals for budget policy over the next several years 
these goals if realized will be attained without any new tax 
measures and should result in a federal deficit that continues to 
decline significantly and consistently 
we believe budget process reform should be an integral part of 
any deficit reduction plan any agreement on the budget should be 
accompanied by process reform to rebuild public confidence in 
national fiscal and monetary policy 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890301-0146 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
 
the national economic commission was given the responsibility for 
making specific bipartisan recommendations regarding 
methods to reduce the federal budget deficit while promoting 
economic growth and encouraging saving and capital formation and 
a means of ensuring that the burden of achieving 
deficitreduction goals does not undermine economic growth and is 
not borne disproportionately by any one economic group social 
group region or state 
deficit reduction is a relatively shortterm objective in that 
the goal is to achieve a balanced budget within five years 
promoting economic growth implies a perspective that extends into 
the 21st century 
the realities of the political constraints faced by the 
commission during the presidential election and transition period 
left no serious possibility of carrying out the first responsibility 
on a bipartisan basis 
the democratic members of the commission concluded reluctantly 
and sadly that the republican members understandable desire to 
support the new presidents plan for achieving deficit reduction 
precluded any likelihood of bipartisan agreement 
the constraints he imposed and his flexible freeze plan are 
plainly and simply inconsistent with ensuring that the burden of 
deficit reduction does not fall disproportionately on any one 
economic group social group region or state 
the fact remains however that the majority of commissioners 
believe that our national savings rate is too low and that 
continuing large budget deficits and huge seemingly intractable 
trade deficits threaten the nations longterm prospects for strong 
economic growth the views in part ii of our report are directed 
toward these longerrun concerns 
what is at stake is how we as a nation enter the 21st century we 
can either slouch into the next century or we can march into it all 
flags flying our future posture will depend upon whether in 
hamiltons term we get our political arithmetic in order in the 
next five years 
getting our political arithmetic in order means achieving budget 
balance by fiscal year 1993 anything earlier being wishful 
thinking and moving into surpluses thereafter the surplus goals 
are readily identifiable they should be approximately equal to the 
combined surplus of the social security trust funds 
there is no option in the sense of an alternative use for the 
surpluses the revenue stream to finance the surplus already exists 
in the form of payroll taxes that are high enough to put the social 
security system on a partially funded basis 
if the present practice of using these surpluses to pay for 
current consumption continues the pressure to return to a 
payasyougo basis will become irresistible and the payroll 
taxes will be returned to a payasyougo level 
on the other hand if we can summon the political will to save 
the surplus we will transform our economy and secure our future 
beyond any present expectations 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
