thousands of mourners wept openly 
wednesday at a funeral for 38 sinhalese men women and children who 
were shot and hacked to death by tamil rebels this week police said 
the crowd of about 2500 sinhalese rice paddy farmers flocked to 
welikande a remote jungle village about 100 miles northeast of 
colombo to mourn victims of monday nights massacre 
they dispersed peacefully after the ceremony a police official 
said 
the government led by president ranasinghe premadasa was 
represented at the joint burial by foreign minister ranjan wijeratne 
and defense secretary general sepala attygalle according to a 
police officer who spoke on condition of anonymity 
the victims were buried in graves in an abandoned rice paddy 
funeral expenses including the cost of coffins were paid by the 
government 
almost every home has hoisted white flags to mourn the deaths 
there is tension in the village but police and soldiers are on 
alert the police sergeant said 
the victims of the massacre were all from sinhalese rice paddy 
farming families most came to welikande in the early 1980s as part 
of a resettlement program after their homes were flooded by the 
mahaveli hydroelectric dam and irrigation project 
the sergeant said that tuesday night a child died of wounds 
suffered in the attack bringing the death toll to 38 22 men five 
women and 11 children 
police tuesday blamed the attack on the liberation tigers of 
tamil eelam the most powerful of the tamil guerrilla groups that 
have been waging a separatist war against the sinhalese majority 
since 1983 more than 8500 people have died since the insurrection 
began 
the tigers denied taking part in the massacre the third in 
northeastern sri lanka in 16 days at least 81 people died in 
attacks on sinhalese civilians 
welikande is in north central province near the border with 
eastern province north central province is predominantly sinhalese 
while eastern province is about evenly divided among sinhalese 
tamils and moslems 
tamil militants say the government has been settling sinhalese in 
the area to tilt the ethnic balance 
tamils who are mostly hindus account for 18 percent of sri 
lankas 16 million people and say they are discriminated against by 
sinhalese in jobs education and the use of the sinhalese language 
sinhalese who are mostly buddhists make up 75 percent of the 
population and dominate the government and military 
