<TEXT>
the supreme court was urged wednesday to grant 
unemployment benefits to a man who says even though he is not a 
member of an organized religious group his christian beliefs dictate 
he not work sundays 
david a french a lawyer for william frazee of peoria ill 
said his clients right to freely exercise his religious beliefs was 
violated by the states denial of unemployment pay 
the belief must be sincerely held and it must be rooted in 
religion said french but he said once state officials accept 
that a persons refusal to work sundays fits those conditions it 
does not matter whether the person belongs to an established 
religious group or sect 
the task for the justices who are expected to decide the case by 
july may have been complicated wednesday when illinois officials 
changed the states approach to the dispute 
the illinois department of employment security previously said 
frazees basis for not working on sundays must be more than an 
individually held religious scruple the belief must be based on 
some tenets or dogma accepted by the individual of some church sect 
or denomination the agency said 
but on wednesday illinois solicitor general robert j ruiz 
argued that frazee was denied unemployment benefits not because of 
the absence of affiliation to a religious group but because his 
belief was personal rather than religious 
the sincerity of a personal belief is not the same as a 
religious belief ruiz said just because someone sincerely 
holds a belief doesnt make it religious 
even if he says that it comes from god asked justice antonin 
scalia in a tone of disbelief it seems to me you are just 
questioning if he was sincere 
the states shift in position also was challenged by justice 
sandra day oconnor 
i dont understand why you are making this argument she 
said adding that the state should have been forthright and 
confessed error 
justice anthony kennedy said the state now seems to be 
encouraging the court to affirm a patently unconstitutional 
ruling 
and justice thurgood marshall said the state appeared to be 
asking the court to decide that frazees beliefs were not sincerely 
religious even though lower courts and state agencies had not 
questioned frazees sincerity 
frazee was disqualified from receiving unemployment benefits 
after he turned down a temporary job assignment in 1984 that would 
have required him to work wednesdays through sundays 
he said as a christian he believed nonemergency work on sunday 
is forbidden 
a state appeals court ruled against frazee it said the 
injunction against sunday labor must be found in a tenet or dogma of 
an established religious sect frazee does not profess to be a 
member of any such sect 
ruiz made no attempt wednesday to defend that reasoning instead 
he said frazee failed to provide enough evidence that his refusal to 
work sundays was predicated on a sincerely held religious belief 
this gentleman may have sincere beliefs ruiz said but 
there is not enough evidence to support it 
the supreme court has held three times previously that states may 
not deny unemployment benefits to people who refuse work because of 
religious scruples but in all three cases the workers based their 
claims on adherence to the teachings of an established religious 
sect 
most recently the court ruled in 1987 that florida authorities 
violated a seventhday adventists religious freedom by denying her 
unemployment pay because she refused to work on saturdays 
