communities should be allowed to protect 
younger teenagers by banning anyone over 18 from dance halls that 
cater to minors the supreme court was told wednesday 
dallas is attacking the juvenile crime problem and the 
influence older people can have on juveniles craig lee hopkins 
argued in urging reinstatement of the texas citys age limits for 
patronizing certain types of dance halls 
hopkins said local governments do not infringe on peoples right 
to associate with whom they please by imposing such bans 
there is no constitutional right of association reaching a 
dance hall he said even if there were such a right hopkins 
added the dallas ordinance still served the compelling interest of 
protecting younger teenagers 
but lawyer daniel sheehan jr representing a dallas dance hall 
owner said we are asking the court to recognize the right to 
associate even if the purpose is social 
although the word association does not appear in the 
constitution a long series of supreme court decisions have 
recognized such a right including political and familial 
associations 
but the court has never said that such constitutional protection 
extends to social or recreational associations as well 
a texas appeals court recognized such a right in 1987 when it 
struck down the dallas ordinance that licensed certain dance halls 
on the condition only teens aged 14 to 18 be admitted as patrons 
the ordinance made exceptions for parents legal guardians and 
dance hall employees 
the city appealed to the nations highest court a decision is 
expected by july 
all nine justices asked questions during a lively hourlong 
argument session wednesday 
chief justice william h rehnquist and justices antonin scalia 
and sandra day oconnor seemed most impressed by hopkins arguments 
that even if 14yearolds have a right to associate with people 
older than 18 the city may create a safe harbor by inhibiting 
that right in dance halls 
at one point a seemingly dubious rehnquist asked sheehan why the 
dance hall age limits are any less constitutional than statutory 
rape laws making it a crime to have sex with a minor 
the dallas ordinance was challenged successfully in state courts 
by charles m stanglin who operates the twilight skating rink 
stanglin has a class e dance hall license issued to those 
dance halls catering to minors 
he divided the floor of his skating rink so that patrons dance or 
skate to the same music in full view of one another people over 18 
can be admitted to the skating rink but not to the dance hall 
contending that the ordinance may betray many dallas residents 
religiously based bias against dancing sheehan asked if the 
problem is older teens corrupting younger teens why are they only 
barred on a dance floor 
scalia smiling broadly suggested that the city may be moving 
on roller rinks next one evil at a time 
justice harry a blackmun voiced surprise when the citys lawyer 
said about 500 dance halls hold licenses 
do they do anything else in dallas blackmun asked 
the case is dallas vs stanglin 871848 
