<TEXT>
industrial nations must pursue noninflationary 
economic growth to stimulate world trade and provide growing markets 
for their own exports and those of lessdeveloped countries the 
bush administration said wednesday in a report to congress 
the report from the treasury department and the office of the 
us trade representative said the united states and its major 
trading partners were committed to making the changes needed to 
reduce imbalances in world trade 
germany and japan both countries with large trade surpluses 
need to take steps to ensure open and growing domestic markets the 
report said 
the united states meanwhile is committed to substantial 
federal budget deficit reductions improving its international 
competitiveness and bolstering its savings rate it said 
the report noted that most economies are structured in ways that 
can hinder international efforts to coordinate monetary fiscal and 
exchange rate policies to promote world trade 
it said the industrial nations agreed at the toronto economic 
summit last year to pursue specific reforms that would reduce such 
barriers through steps such as cutting subsidies that impede the 
international flow of resources reforming tax systems that 
discourage innovation and reducing burdensome regulations 
such a course is well suited to producing mediumterm solutions 
to what are after all mediumterm problems the report said 
the report projected that without policy changes japans trade 
surplus in goods and services would drop significantly in the 
next two years from about 80 billion this year while germany with 
export growth rebounding would see its overall surplus largely 
unchanged 
englands ballooning of its trade deficit in 1988 is unlikely to 
be reversed and france italy and canada should collectively have 
about the same deficit in 1990 that they did in 1988 it said 
the united states meanwhile expects to see increases in exports 
exceed growth in imports although rising payments on the national 
debt will hold back the overall reductions in the trade deficit 
the us trade deficit in 1988 posted its first improvement since 
1980 narrowing to 13734 billion from an alltime high of 17032 
billion in 1987 
the report said lessdeveloped countries also must move to 
promote world trade these countries especially those that are 
heavily in debt must adopt policies that support domestic growth 
reduce inflation and encourage support from banks and international 
financial institutions it said 
the trade projection report was required under the omnibus trade 
act of 1988 
