britains merchandise trade deficit widened to 209 
billion pounds or 363 billion in january from a revised deficit 
of 176 billion pounds in december the government said wednesday 
januarys trade gap compared with a deficit of 145 billion 
pounds in january 1988 the department of trade and industry said 
the financial markets had been expecting a deficit of about 185 
million pounds and the treasury moved quickly to say they 
shouldnt put too much emphasis on the figures 
monthly trade figures can be very erratic and among the 
last indicators to respond to a tightening of monetary policy 
said a treasury spokesman speaking anonymously in keeping with 
british custom 
the pound fell slightly on the news from 17350 to 17300 
bryan gould trade spokesman for the opposition labor party said 
the figures show britain is now an economy which cannot pay its 
way and which is falling further and further behind in the 
competitive race 
the figures showed exports totaled a record 737 billion pounds 
in january up from 69 billion pounds in december and up from 64 
billion pounds in january 1988 
imports totalled a record 947 billion pounds in january up from 
866 billion pounds in december and up from 78 billion pounds in 
january 1988 
the december merchandise trade deficit was previously reported as 
166 billion pounds the government said the upward revision in the 
december figures was due mainly to a revision in the seasonal 
adjustments for 1988 
with januarys trade in invisible items which covers services 
overseas investment earnings and official transfer payments 
estimated to be in surplus by 400 million pounds britains current 
account showed a deficit of 169 billion pounds compared with a 
revised deficit of 136 billion pounds in december 
</TEXT>
