drexel burnham lambert inc voluntarily agreed to 
terminate michael milken and withhold his 1988 pay of more than 100 
million despite claims by the prominent bond trader that drexel was 
coerced into the provisions the government said 
in court papers filed tuesday federal prosecutors rejected a 
motion by milken to have drexels firms landmark securities fraud 
settlement with the justice department thrown out or modified 
because it violates milkens rights 
the coercion issue is at the heart of the first legal challenge 
to the settlement milken claims that drexel was forced to resolve 
the case or face racketeering charges that included freezing the 
investment firms multibilliondollar assets 
milken alleged that the government forced drexel to have him 
dismissed and his 1988 compensation most of it in a bonus that 
would far surpass 100 million withheld 
acting us attorney benito romano called the charge of coercion 
nothing short of absurd 
to argue that drexel a highly sophisticated investment banking 
firm represented by numerous highly qualified attorneys was 
incapable of making a voluntary choice in this matter strains 
credulity romano wrote 
in an accompanying affidavit drexel chief executive officer 
frederick h joseph said the investment firm entered into the plea 
agreement with the justice department voluntarily and without 
coercion after consulting with counsel 
the statement while technically accurate since drexel endorsed 
the total pact appeared to be at odds with earlier statements by 
the company that it disputed portions of the agreement and fought to 
have provisions on milken withdrawn 
joseph also was quoted in earlier court papers as saying the 
milken provisions were unfair and horrendous and were 
inserted at the governments insistence 
drexel in december agreed to pay a record 650 million fine and 
