the chairman of the federal communications 
commission today rejected a senators request to delay a 
controversial overhaul of atampts rate structure despite widespread 
congressional criticism of the proposed action 
fcc chairman dennis patrick told sen james exon dneb he will 
press ahead at a march 16 commission meeting with the plan to change 
the way american telephone amp telegraph charges customers he said 
the part of the proposal covering interstate service could go into 
effect july 1 
exon asked patrick at the hearing of the senate commerce science 
and transportation subcommittee on communications if he would 
postpone consideration of the rate cap plan until two vacancies 
on the fivemember fcc are filled by the bush administration 
the commission has been two members short since the beginning of 
last year and president bush has yet to announce choices for the 
open slots 
it is extraordinarily important to restructure the incentives 
that we give this industry patrick told exon today we have to 
begin to send a message the sooner we start on that the better 
