subcommittee the plan could save residential customers 700 million 
in the next four years while giving atampt the incentive to streamline 
and modernize 
but subcommittee chairman ed markey dmass asked patrick why 
all the people who are purported to benefit from this plan still 
oppose it and why all those who are supposed to be regulated by it 
are clamoring for its immediate implementation 
the fcc proposal would change the two decadesold rate of 
return regulation that allows atampt certain specified profits 
beyond its costs 
the new plan what patrick called incentive regulation 
would place a cap on what atampt could charge customers but would 
allow the company to keep any funds after costs as profit 
congress let the plan die last year because of concerns that 
windfall profits could result at the expense of consumers but 
patrick is moving ahead with it after making changes he says meet 
congressional concerns 
weve made several changes to satisfy their concerns and well 
continue to discuss them said patrick but the commission will 
consider the pricing matter on the 16th 
patricks july 1 target leaves congressional critics little time 
to pass an alternative that precludes the fcc 
at this point we dont have a concensus said markey 
rep bill richardson dnm said congress has left a vacuum 
that patrick is filling with his action he urged his colleagues to 
preserve our role in the regulatory process 
and rep rick boucher dva told reporters that patrick should 
postpone an fcc vote for a second time in new of the bipartisan 
nature of the concerns expressed at tuesdays hearing 
