<TEXT>
xerox corp introduced three new copiers 
today including two lowvolume models and a copier with a beveled 
edge that can make copies from books without ruining bindings 
the machines were displayed at a news conference at the companys 
major manufacturing center in the rochester suburb of webster xerox 
is based in stamford conn 
the lowvolume copiers the 5012 and the 5014 make 12 copies a 
minute and come with xeroxs unique threeyear warranty on parts and 
labor and a copy cartridge guarantee 
xerox has always enjoyed a strong position in the mid and 
highvolume copier segments but has not fared as well in the highly 
competitive lowvolume and personal copier markets 
these new machines represent the companys attempt to increase 
its presence in the lowvolume market which includes machines that 
make up to 30 copies a minute said paul cahn vice president of 
reprographics product support for xeroxs us marketing group 
were aiming to set the industry benchmark for quality and 
value in the lowvolume range cahn said 
the 5012 costs 2325 the 5014 which has reduction and 
enlargement capabilities costs 2850 
the companys other new copier the 5042 was designed for book 
copying mostly with the library industry in mind cahn said 
it has a 35degree slanted copying surface and a hinged cover 
that will follow the shape of a book or other bound material instead 
of squashing it down it makes 35 copies a minute 
xerox officials said their studies found that in 1985 libraries 
spent about 40 million to repair broken book bindings and they 
believe the 5042 machine will help save bindings 
the machine also features a versatile vending attachment that 
will accept coins bills and special vending cards 
we have offered vending before but it was just coins said 
jim miller xeroxs manager of decentralized product marketing 
and librarians told us they were tired of spending their whole day 
making change for people 
the 5042 costs 9470 
all of the machines are available to buy or rent immediately 
