<TEXT>
the government issued two reports today suggesting economic 
growth is weakening contrary to a fourthquarter 1988 assessment 
issued tuesday that signaled rising inflation and an unabated us 
appetite for foreign goods 
the commerce department said americans personal income shot up 
18 percent in january the biggest increase in more than a year 
but that the pace of consumer spending was nearly unchanged after a 
strong gain in december 
a slowdown in consumer spending would be welcome news to some 
because of worries that demand has been outstripping the production 
capabilities of factories already coping with high operating rates 
and tight labor markets 
in another report the commerce department said construction 
spending rose 04 percent in january the weakest performance since 
october rising interest rates have dampened activity in most areas 
of the construction business with fixedrate mortgages averaging 
nearly 11 percent 
the reports came a day after the department released figures on 
fourthquarter growth that worried economists because it suggested 
pickup in inflation partly because of the summer drought 
while the overall growth figure of 2 percent was unchanged from 
an initial report a month ago the report also showed that the 
countrys trade imbalance worsened even more than previously 
estimated imports grew at an annual rate of 13 percent swamping a 
7 percent gain in exports 
consumer spending rose at a robust 35 percent annual rate too 
fast given constraints on production resulting from tight labor 
markets and high factory operating rates economists said the jump 
in consumer spending which went primarily to bigticket items such 
as cars also showed americans are still spending and borrowing to 
buy foreign goods 
in other economic news tuesday a real estate trade group 
reported sales of existing homes fell 74 percent in january the 
biggest decline in two years but housing industry experts said the 
drop reflected a return to more normal buying patterns following a 
december sales spurt 
the national association of realtors said that existing 
singlefamily homes were sold at a seasonally adjusted annual rate 
of 363 million units in january after 57 percent rise in december 
to a rate of 392 million 
none of the reports had much impact on the financial markets on 
wall street stock prices rose slightly in what analysts called a 
reflex response to its sharp declines of the previous week bond 
prices a sensitive barometer of the economy fell sightly and the 
dollar finished mixed against foreign currencies 
</TEXT>
