<TEXT>
soybean futures prices closed sharply lower 
wednesday on the chicago board of trade amid forecasts for rain in 
argentinas soybean fields and signs that supplies may not be as 
tight as previously feared 
wheat futures advanced modestly due to an increase in export 
business while corn futures finished mixed 
soybean futures plunged in the sessions final 10 minutes 
following forecasts for rain in argentina later today and over the 
weekend 
the selling also reflected an increase wednesday in the number of 
notices of intent to deliver soybeans against the march contract 
a greater number of notices indicates a greater willingness among 
commercial traders to sell physical soybeans which suggests an 
easing of supply fears 
soybean delivery notices posted wednesday morning totaled 92 
million bushels compared with 44 million bushels on tuesday the 
first notice day for the march contract 
wheat gained strength from the agriculture departments decision 
to target iraq for sales of 1 million metric tons of us wheat at 
subsidized prices and from reports that the soviet union was 
bidding for 500000 metric tons of subsidized us wheat 
at the close wheat was 1 cent to 4 cents higher with the 
contract for delivery in march at 439 a bushel corn was cent 
lower to cent higher with march at 271 a bushel oats were 1 
cents to 2 cents lower with march at 203 a bushel soybeans were 
3 cents to 12 cents lower with march at 750 a bushel 
