<TEXT>
xerox corp hopes a copier introduced 
wednesday will save the encyclopedias dictionaries and other books 
in libraries around the country from brokenbinding syndrome 
the xerox 5042 has a slanted edge and a hinged cover that allow a 
book or other bound material to be laid flat without squashing or 
stretching the binding 
weve responded very directly to a market need said paul 
cahn vice president of reprographics product support for xeroxs 
us marketing group 
xerox officials said their studies found that libraries spent 
about 40 million in 1985 to repair broken book bindings 
this is very much of a niche kind of product but its the kind 
of thing that will give xerox a presence in places it wants to be 
like universities and libraries where a lot of people will see 
their name said bob sostilio a copierindustry analyst with 
dataquest inc of san jose calif 
the 5042 makes 35 copies a minute and can make reductions and 
enlargements it sells for 9470 
the machine also features a vending attachment that accepts 
coins bills and magnetic cards 
we have offered vending before but it was just coins said 
jim miller xeroxs manager of decentralized product marketing 
and librarians told us they were tired of spending their whole day 
making change for people 
the american library association asked copier companies to come 
up with a copier that wouldnt damage books and would make better 
copies of bound materials 
