coastal corp of houston and arkla inc of 
shreveport la announced a major pipeline expansion wednesday that 
will open up markets in the northeast and the midwest to the 
prolific arkoma basin in eastern oklahoma 
officials said the the project will ultimately mean an extra 450 
million cubic feet per day of natural gas can be moved to the 
midwest and northeast 
they estimated that would increase the sales of oklahoma gas by 
300 million 
officials said most of the capacity expansion will come from a 
new 200mile pipeline originating in latimer county in eastern 
oklahoma and terminating in jefferson county ark 
they said the 30inch diameter pipeline will provide substantial 
additional capacity across oklahoma and arkansas to the southeast 
mainline of anr pipeline co a coastal subsidiary 
estimated cost of the new pipeline was set at 120 million 
officials said it could be in service by as early as mid1990 
the announcement was made at a news conference attended by 
oklahoma gov henry bellmon james f cordes executive vice 
president of coastal and mike bracy president of arklas pipeline 
group 
cordes said officials believe the new pipeline will allow 
oklahoma gas to be sold at a competitive price with natural gas from 
canada 
bracy said the first phase of the project will kick off next 
month 
from coastals prospective these agreements have three major 
benefits cordes said first we will substantially improve our 
ability to move gas out of oklahoma by providing greatly expanded 
transportation and pipeline links between our southwest and 
southeast pipeline facilities 
second by using our newly proposed connections in ohio to the 
major pipelines serving the northeast oklahoma producers will gain 
direct access to this major growing gas market 
third our anr pipeline subsidiary will gain access to the 
increasingly important gas supplies in the arkoma basis to meet the 
requirements of its customers in the future 
bracy said the project allows arkla to strengthen its access to 
new markets while at the same time increasing the efficiency of 
our existing pipeline system which will benefit our current 
customers and producers 
the extra sales of oklahoma gas will mean an additional 21 
million in gross production taxes for the state officials said 
those taxes go principally to the state teacher retirement program 
